The Mexican food is globally known for being one of the most delicious and varied cuisines in the world, from the north to the south you will find even different version of the same dish, the clue is to bear on mind that every place you visit has its very particular cooking tradition, usually called ‚Äúsaz√≥n‚Äù. So, take the following into consideration.

1.	The corn is King.- This ingredient, having been used as the foundation of the Mexican cuisine,  has several presentations commonly transformed into tortillas, tlacoyos, queasadillas and tlayudas. Even our ancestors have made different beverages from it, like atole, tejuino and pozol, which are usually served at street corners.
2.	Barbacoa is a must. - This typical dish made of lamb, is one of the most popular and most well-seasoned dishes here in Mexico, a special tip is to have barbacoa accompanied by ‚Äúconsom√©‚Äù that is broth result of a long-time cooking technique that keeps all the flavor from de lamb.
3.	Cochinita pibil.- Coming from the south, this dish made of pork meat, is a pre-hispanic recipe that mixes ingredients like achiote, orange juice, garlic, cumin, salt and peper, the interesting thing is that all the ingredients are wrapped in banana leaves, that is said to give an additional flavor.

Wherever you go make the most of your time and enjoy all the dishes you can, just be aware that Mexicans have been eating spicy food for centuries and probably trying some dishes could be a ‚Äúhot‚Äù experience for you.

text:
Mexico -> Eating habits

Mexican food is worldwide renowned, mainly because it has a broad variety of dishes, both savory and sweet. Being on top 3 international cuisine for over a decade now, it highlights the wide range of ingredients that the country possesses as well as the impressive background it helds, prehispanic as well as modern.
Having said that, let‚Äôs go over a few habits that are well-known over Mexico and you'd like to know when visiting.

1. Tacos. Mexico is recognized all over the world for their tacos, there‚Äôs an enormous variety of fillings in them, so don‚Äôt be shy and try them all. 
2. Beer. There are many brands, commercial and artisanal, though the big one is Corona which is enjoyed internationally, since this is its home, have it a go as soon as you can and ¬°Salud!
3. Have yourself some dessert! Keep that sweet tooth satisfied as you can find amazing cakes, puddings and ice creams, each for every region in our country.
4. Tips. It's customary to leave a tip when you like the service, it commonly isn't included at the end of your service, but there are some places that do so. Always check your bill!

Table manners can be similar to the ones you may already know, but there‚Äôs something very distinctive about Mexican people and that is that we can be loud during meals, it won‚Äôt be unusual if you suddenly feel on a different place than a restaurant, more like a party. 

Enjoy your stay and visit again soon!

text:
Mexico‚Äôs culinary landscape is rich in flavors and traditions, making it an essential part of the cultural experience for business visitors. So, for visitors understanding local eating habits and etiquette can help navigate social interactions and strengthen professional relationships. 

In Mexico, everyone follows a dining structured schedule. For example, having breakfast is usually enjoyed between 7:00 AM and 10:00 AM, often featuring dishes like chilaquiles, tamales, pan dulce, eggs with juice, hot chocolate, coffee or fresh fruit. 
The main meal occurs between 2:00 PM and 5:00 PM and typically includes soup, a main course with rice and beans, and dessert. Dishes like pozole, enchiladas, enfrijoladas or barbacoa are also commonly enjoyed at this time.
And for dinner, it is lighter and usually served between 8:00 PM and 10:00 PM, consisting of tacos, quesadillas, tortas, ‚Äúlight‚Äù. 

Business dining etiquette is crucial. The host generally pays, though offering to contribute is polite. For example, tipping 10‚Äì15% is standard and for sure; sharing dishes. Because it reinforces a communal dining experience. In addition that business meals often serve as a time for socializing, making conversation as important as the food itself. Showing appreciation for the meal and the host‚Äôs hospitality is always well received
To sum up, in my opinion, visitors should try tacos al pastor, mole, quesadillas, cochinita pibil along with street food like elotes, esquites and gorditas. Drinks such as horchata, jamaica, mezcal, and caf√© de olla offer a taste of Mexico‚Äôs beverage culture. However, it is wise to be mindful of spice levels, as some dishes can be quite hot for those unaccustomed to them.

The Mexican Food Experience. 
Mexican gastronomy is widely known for it's diversity on lucious, spicy flavors, textures and colors which embodies the people that make them everyday in their homes. Having said that, there are many other staple foods Mexico has to offer to travellers even if their visit isn't focused on tourism. 

- Tacos: The most iconic Mexican dish across the world; Made with soft corn tortillas they can be prepared with any kind of meat or be exchanged for vegetables and other non-carnical options for vegetarians and vegans. It is generally served with chopped parsley, onion sprinkled on top, and for those that want to add more flavor to it they can squeeze lime juice and have some red or green sauce as dressings. 

- Mixiote: The mixiote is one of the tastiest and hardest dishes to prepare succesfully. Prepared with pork loin and a great variety of sp√¨ces such as oregano, laurel leafs, pepper, vinegar along with a marinade of guajillo and ancho chiles is traditionally cooked in a hole on the ground wrapped in maguey leafs. The result is one of the tastiest foods in the country. 

- Pozole: A broth usually made out of pork bones and meat althogh it can be prepared with chicken. It is prepared with maize kernels called hominy and is generally served with lettuce, chopped onion and radish. It can be accompanied with tostadas with sour cream and cheese on top.

text:
Mexican cuisine is one of the most diverse ones, from region to region it has a vast extense of meals with an explosion of flavours and textures for all type of visitors, including businesspeople who do not have too much time to explore the city. 

To have a Mexican gastronomy experience but with limited time, these are 3 unforgettable dishes served in most of restaurants and are nearby the business areas such as in Reforma or Santa Fe: 
‚Ä¢	Pozole: this is a broth, specially made of pork but may also be chicken. This dish is prepared with maize kernels called hominy, and can be served with lettuce, chopped onion, radish (sliced or chopped), a pinch of oregano and a squirt of lime juice to boost its flavour. Depending on the region, this dish is accompanied by toasted tortillas with sour cream. 
‚Ä¢	Mole: this type of sauce is highly elaborated with a mixture of chilis, chocolate, and other spices. This highly appreciated gastronomy delicacy is enjoyed in big celebrations like weddings, birthdays or any other special occasion. Its variety is what makes it special: it may be served with chicken or pork, rice, as ‚Äúenmoladas‚Äù (a chicken wrap dipped in mole). 
‚Ä¢	Chiles en nogada: this is a very special Mexican dish which was allegedly created using the flag‚Äôs colours: the green from chili, the white from the walnut cream, the red from the pomegranate. This dish combines the sweet from the fruit and cream with the savoury of the chili and its filling, which is minced meat. 

After having tried these Mexican dishes in a business trip, you will be back for more. This time it is very likely you will travel for pleasure.

text:
Try the Mexican Experience!
Mexican cuisine is acknowledged for its variety, rich flavors, colours and spicy ingredients. Having said this, if you are on a business trip, apart from feeling welcome and in a hospitable atmosphere, you‚Äôll be able to witness the best culinary experience. However, understanding dining customs and table manners can boost your experience:
1.	Greeting: When arriving at a restaurant greet everyone with a handshake, a warm smile and wait for the hostess to book 
2.	Punctuality: Generally being a bit late is acceptable as Mexicans are flexible with time, nonetheless, for business meals, it is respectful to be punctual. 
3.	Starting the Meal: Waiting for all the members to initiate the meal as a matter of respect.
4.	Conversation: Engaging in light conversation is advisable rather than going through personal or controversial topics. 
5.	Eating Pace: Taking your time to enjoy the meal is valuable as Mexicans value the dining experience.
6.	Compliments: Complimenting the food and hospitality is a sign of respect and gratitude.
7.	Drinking: Refusing entirely can be seen as impolite. However, you do not need to consume more than you are comfortable with.
8.	Ending the Meal: Wait for the host to signal the end of the meal. Often, a small gesture like placing their napkin on the table indicates that the meal is over.
Conclusion

Mexican Eating Habits ‚Äì A Quick Guide for Business Visitors

Mexican food is known to be intense, varied and delicious, and sharing it with locals can be quite a mesmerizing experience. Now, in a business context, there are some recommendations you might want to follow when eating with colleagues or clients, as it can cultivate good relationships and promote smooth interactions.

1. Don¬¥t rush ‚Äì Often being slowly paced, meals in Mexico might take longer than in some other countries, so so make sure to relax and enjoy it.

2. Food is culture ‚Äì People in Mexico have a high regard for their food, as it represents their culture. Feeling proud about this, they will probably offer you to try different kinds of food. It can be rude not to accept too many of these offerings, so make sure to accept at least a small amount of it. 

3. Salud! ‚Äì Mexico has a wide variety of artisanal alcoholic drinks and cocktails, commonly taken during meals. You may be offered to try some of them but be careful because these can be strong. You can drink, but moderately. And don¬¥t forget to say ‚Äú¬°Salud!‚Äù before taking the first sip. 

4. ‚ÄúIt¬¥s my treat‚Äù ‚Äì Bear in mind that if you get invited to a business meal in Mexico, the host will most likely pay for the whole bill, as an expression of courtesy. You can try to pitch in, but they will probably try to stop you, so don¬¥t feel bad about it and only express your gratitude to them. 

By considering these recommendations, you¬¥ll feel in a more comfortable atmosphere by also showing respect for Mexican culture. Have a great experience!

text:
The world is a diverse and rich tapestry of culinary delights, offering a wide array of mouthwatering dishes. While taste preferences are subjective, here are some of the tastiest foods from different corners of the globe:

Pizza (Italy): With its thin, crispy crust, tangy tomato sauce, and a myriad of delicious toppings, pizza is a global favorite. Whether it's the classic Margherita or a creative combination of flavors, this Italian creation never fails to satisfy.

Sushi (Japan): Sushi is a culinary art form that combines delicate flavors and textures. From fresh sashimi to perfectly seasoned rice rolls, sushi offers a harmonious blend of ingredients like raw or cooked seafood, vegetables, and pickled delights.

Tacos (Mexico): Bursting with vibrant flavors, tacos are a staple of Mexican cuisine. Soft or crispy tortillas filled with marinated meats, grilled vegetables, zesty salsas, and toppings like avocado and cilantro create a delicious explosion of taste.

Pad Thai (Thailand): A quintessential Thai dish, Pad Thai is a stir-fried noodle dish that balances sweet, sour, and savory flavors. It typically combines rice noodles, shrimp or chicken, bean sprouts, peanuts, lime, and a tangy tamarind sauce.

Gelato (Italy): Gelato, the Italian version of ice cream, is known for its dense and creamy texture. It comes in a multitude of flavors, from classic favorites like chocolate and pistachio to unique combinations like stracciatella (chocolate chip) or fragola (strawberry).

Peking Duck (China): Peking Duck is a beloved Chinese dish that features tender, succulent roast duck with crispy skin. Served with thin pancakes, hoisin sauce, and spring onions, this dish offers a delightful blend of flavors and textures.

Paella (Spain): Originating from the region of Valencia, paella is a rice dish that showcases the vibrant colors and flavors of Spain. Combining saffron-infused rice, various meats or seafood, and a medley of vegetables, it's a true culinary delight.

Croissant (France): A buttery and flaky French pastry, the croissant is a breakfast favorite around the world. Whether enjoyed plain or filled with chocolate, almond paste, or ham and cheese, this iconic treat is a symbol of French craftsmanship.

BBQ Ribs (United States): Tender and smoky BBQ ribs are a highlight of American cuisine. Slow-cooked and basted with tangy barbecue sauce, these meaty delights are a mouthwatering indulgence that satisfies meat lovers.

Chocolate (Global): Chocolate, with its rich and velvety taste, is beloved by people worldwide. From dark and intense to creamy and milky, chocolate delights the palate in various forms, including bars, truffles, and decadent desserts.

These are just a few examples of the tastiest foods in the world, each offering a unique culinary experience. Exploring different cuisines allows us to discover a world of flavors and expand our culinary horizons. So, grab your fork and embark on a delicious adventure!
